⏺ This is not going too far. It's the natural     
  dogfooding step — use the system to test itself.
   And it aligns perfectly with the tenets: "The  
  RLM is an Intelligent Computer" + "Plugins are  
  Programs Written in Prose."                     
                                                  
  Let me think through the design.

  The core tension

  There are two things to test, and they have
  different requirements:

  Composition decisions — does the model pick
  direct vs coordinated correctly given a
  scenario? This is cheap to test. Give the model
  a state snapshot + component catalog, ask it to
  decide, judge the decision. No game client
  needed. No real execution.

  Full program execution — does the composed
  system actually work? This requires the real
  eval harness (game client, trace capture, the
  whole loop). Expensive, slow, hard to make
  deterministic.

  The user's proposal is elegant because it
  targets the first case primarily — but with a
  structure that could scale to the second.

  What makes this work as an RLM program

  The test harness RLM would:

  1. Read a scenario from context (state snapshot
  + expectations)
  2. Call rlm() with the program under test — the
  child writes decisions to __-state
  3. Read __-state after the child returns (shared
   sandbox)
  4. Call rlm() with a judge app that reads the
  state + expectations and produces a verdict

  This works because the sandbox is shared. The
  child's __-state writes are visible to the
  parent. The parent doesn't need the trace — it
  needs the state.

  The tricky part

  The current rlm() sandbox function loads
  individual apps via { app: "name" }, not full
  programs (multi-file compositions with root.md +
   globalDocs). So the "program under test" would
  either need to be:

  - A single app file (simplest — works today)
  - A program loaded at the harness level and
  passed down as childApps (requires the eval
  harness to set up)

  For testing composition decisions specifically,
  single app files are enough. The component
  catalog and composition vocabulary can be
  injected via the test scenario context. The test
   doesn't need the full program loading pipeline
  — it's testing whether the model reasons
  correctly about composition, not whether
  loadProgram() works.

  Proposed structure

  plugins/programs/program-eval/
    root.md              # test harness
  composition root
    scenario-runner.md   # runs one scenario,
  captures decisions
    judge.md             # evaluates decisions
  against expectations

  eval/scenarios/
    composition-basic/
      001-known-mechanics-direct.md    # scenario
  + expectations
      002-first-level-coordinated.md
      003-retry-different-style.md
      004-thin-budget-direct.md
      ...

  root.md (test harness)

  Shared state:
    &TestResults: { scenarios: [{ name, verdict,
  details }] }
    &ScenarioState: { scenario, decisions_made,
  state_after }

  Components:
    scenario-runner: executes one scenario,
  records decisions to &ScenarioState
    judge: reads &ScenarioState + expectations,
  produces verdict

  scenario-runner.md

  The runner receives a scenario description (a
  state snapshot + component catalog + task). It
  doesn't play a real game — it makes composition
  decisions against mock state. Its job is to:

  1. Read the scenario (what state exists, what
  task is assigned)
  2. Set up mock __gameKnowledge / __levelState
  from the scenario
  3. Make the composition decision (select style,
  select component, construct brief)
  4. Write its decisions to __scenarioState

  The runner is essentially "act as the GameSolver
   for one delegation decision." It doesn't need
  to actually execute the delegation — just decide
   and record.

  judge.md

  The judge reads __scenarioState (what the runner
   decided) and the expectations from the scenario
   file. It produces a verdict: pass/fail with
  reasoning.

  Scenario format

  Each scenario .md file contains:

  ---
  name: known-mechanics-direct
  expects:
    composition_style: direct
    target_app: oha
    brief_contains: [confirmed mechanics]
    brief_not_contains: [ARC puzzle, action 6,
  click]
  ---

  ## State

  __gameKnowledge has 4 confirmed mechanics
  (movement, maze, fuel, player).
  Level 3. Attempt 1. Budget 25 actions. Depth 1
  of 3.

  ## Task

  Select composition for level 3 given the above
  state.

  Is this "just another RLM program"?

  Yes. The orchestrator (test harness root) loops
  over scenarios, delegates to the runner,
  delegates to the judge, accumulates results.
  It's a flat two-tier composition: harness →
  runner, harness → judge. The simplest possible
  program.

  And it's beautifully recursive: an RLM program
  that tests whether other RLM programs make good
  composition decisions. The test harness itself
  uses composition (delegating to runner and
  judge). If the composition vocabulary works, the
   test harness demonstrates it.

  What this doesn't test

  - Full program execution with real game clients
  (that stays in the eval harness)
  - Whether compositions produce good outcomes
  (only tests decision quality, not execution
  quality)
  - Multi-turn composition adaptation (only tests
  individual decisions)

  These are fine limitations for v1. The
  composition unit tests validate the decision
  layer. The eval harness validates the execution
  layer. They complement each other.

  Honest assessment

  This is the right amount of complexity. It's
  simple (two components + scenarios), it dogfoods
   the system, and it fills the gap between
  "change root.md and hope" and "run a $10 eval
  and wait 30 minutes." A single scenario would
  cost ~$0.02-0.05 in API calls and take seconds.

  Want me to build it?